<dl id="n10078g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10078g">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10078g"> 78(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the double <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10078g"><li>FW 471.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qC/lexqC.htm#n10078g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qC/l39qC.htm#n10078g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10078g">MS BL 47482b-59</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:119 <a name="qA3d" href="../../FF/fdra/qda.htm#qC3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qC3d.htm#n10078g">Draft: III&sect;2C.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Nous avons d&eacute;j&agrave; dit que les particuliers pouvaient &ecirc;tre admis &agrave; se servir de la Poste imp&eacute;riale, mais non pas sans conditions. L&apos;autorisation donn&eacute;e par le prince ou en son nom s&apos;appelait diploma, et plus souvent, sous l&apos;empire, litter&aelig; evectionis, lettre de transport ou de voiture. Le dipl&ocirc;me &eacute;tait une sorte de passe-port tirant son nom de sa forme, pli&eacute; <mark>en double</mark> <font color="green">[We have already said that private individuals could use the Imperial Post, but not unconditionally. The authorisation given by the prince himself or on his behalf was called a diploma and, more frequently, in the Empire, <i>litter&aelig; evectionis</i>, letter of transport or of carriage. The diploma was a sort of passport that took its name from its form, for it was folded in two]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 55-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
